Introduction¶

The Movie Database TMDb is a community built movie and TV database. The following data analysis is based on TMDb dataset adapted from the original dataset available in Kaggle. For the purposes of this analysis, I will adopt the name of movie for both movies and TV series.

In [1]:
# importing packages

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline

Data Wrangling¶

After importing the dataset, I will do a recognition and an initial exploration to have the first contact with the data, to know its size or volume, column or variable names, data type, possible missing data, an initial reading for general knowledge about the dataset.
According to the section below, we have 21 variables and 10866 movie records. The variables with the largest amount of null or missing data are: homepage, tagline and keywords.

Of the 4 variables with the largest number of missing data, 2 of them I do not intend to use for this analysis: homepage and tagline. Another variable that will not contribute much to the analysis is imdb_id. So I will exclude them from the temporary dataset that we will create for analysis. There are two types of variables for budget and revenue (data types float64 and int64), both without nulls. I will use the budget and revenue variables of type int64, by personal decision. Without a technical factor that can justify such a decision, I just chose to keep a type of each variable in the dataset that I will use in the analysis.

After summarizing some descriptive statistics generated by the describe method of Pandas we have some initial numbers from our dataset. In this summary, missing values are excluded.
We can see that the oldest movie in the dataset was released in 1960 and the newest one in 2015, with most of the movies being released between mid 2000 and 2015. The average vote score was 5.97, with most of the votes between 5 and 7. Only 1/4 of the movies had more than 145 votes, the movie with the least votes had 10 votes and the one with the most votes obtained 9767 vote records. And more than half of the movies have a budget and revenue as zero.
We can see these numbers reflected in the histogram graphs below.

Preliminary analysis and possible questions¶

My main question to be investigated in the dataset is whether there is a possible relationship between genres of films, their popularity, their revenue and profit. Or what kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues.

First, let's look at histograms of some variables in general to try to discover some pattern or initial insight.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

We can conclude that the Drama genre is one of the most common in the entire dataset. However, among movies with revenues above 100 million, other genres also stand out, such as: Action, Comedy, Adventure and Thriller. In movies with revenues above 1 billion, the two most prominent genres were Action and Adventure.

Investigating more about revenue and other possible relationships¶

Now I will investigate possible relations between revenue and other variables in the dataset, such as popularity, number of votes (vote_count), average grade of votes (vote_average) and even a new variable created from the budget and revenue variables, the profit variable.

# Function to calculate profit from budget and revenue columns
def profit(row):
    return row["revenue"] - row["budget"]

Conclusions¶

We can conclude that the genres that predominate among the films with the highest revenue and profit are those of action, adventure, drama and comedy.
Among the 100 most profitable films, the genres of adventure, action, fantasy and science fiction predominate. Among the 100 best rated films, however without distinguishing by revenue and profit, we have the genres documentary, drama, music, comedy and crime standing out. Possibly these films refer a lot to TV productions.
Analyzing the possible correlations between input variables in the dataset, we can see some correlation between revenue, profit, budget, popularity, number of votes (vote_count) and average vote rating (vote_average).
